Q51: Create a script that will print "Hello World" on Screen ?

#!/bin/bash
echo "Hello World"

Notes : to run this script if this is saved as script1.sh
need to use ./ script1.sh

Q52: Create a script that will print system date and time on Screen ?


Vi datetime.sh

#!/bin/bash
date

Notes: ./ datetime.sh is used to run the script

Q53: Create a script that will take user name as input and then print the same on Screen ?

#!/bin/bash
read -p "enter your name" username
echo $username

Notes: Read command is used to take input from user 
and -p is to prompt something

This can also be done as 

#!/bin/bash
echo "Enter username"
read username
echo $username - $ is used to display ENV variables which are put in by the user


Q54: Create a script that will go to sleep for 60 seconds and then print "Good Bye" on screen ?

#!/bin/bash 
sleep 60 
echo "Good Bye"

Notes: sleep 60 is used to put sleep inbetween operation (waitime) and 60 is the amount of seconds


Q55: Create a script that will create a file with name "devops.txt" and insert the free memory details of your Linux machine in it ?

#!/bin/bash
touch devops.txt
free -m > devops.txt

Notes: Free -m will print the memory status on scree


Q56: Create a script that will create a file with name "disk.txt" and insert the disk utilization details of your Linux machine in that file ?

#!/bin/bash
touch disk.txt
df -h > disk.txt

Notes : df-h is for figuring out the disk utilisation and -h is to show it in human readable format


Q57: Create a script that will print "Even Day" if current date is an even number ?

#!/bin/bash
DATE = 'date+'%d''
if [$DATE%2] -eq 0
then
echo "Even Day"
fi

Notes:
Date is used to get the date and %d is for getting the exact date 
then we use modulus function (%) to compare the remainder and -eq is to compare if output is equal to 
we use "then" function to echo and fi to end the if else conditions







